{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639563"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:06:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:06:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17780"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17780"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10494"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72460"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10494"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17780"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57930"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10164"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24495"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24562"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72460"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EKeratinocytes are the main cellular component of the epidermis and play a crucial role in skin barrier function.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of keratinocytes in the epidermis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Formation of tactile sensations","Production of melanin pigment","Production of vitamin D","Synthesis of keratin proteins","Secretion of sebum"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of keratinocytes is the \u003Cstrong\u003Esynthesis of keratin proteins\u003C/strong\u003E. These structural proteins provide mechanical strength and create a protective barrier against environmental factors, water loss, and pathogen entry.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESpecialised nerve endings in the skin are responsible for \u003Cstrong\u003Eformation of tactile sensations\u003C/strong\u003E, not keratinocytes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of melanin pigment\u003C/strong\u003E is carried out by melanocytes rather than keratinocytes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eproduction of vitamin D\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in the skin, this is a photochemical process rather than a primary keratinocyte function.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecretion of sebum\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by sebaceous glands rather than keratinocytes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKeratinocytes undergo a programmed differentiation process, moving from the basal layer towards the surface while producing increasing amounts of keratin. This results in the formation of the stratum corneum, the outermost protective layer of the skin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Keratinocytes are the predominant cell type in the epidermis, comprising approximately 90% of epidermal cells.","The primary function of keratinocytes is to produce keratin proteins that provide structural support and barrier protection.","Keratinocytes undergo progressive differentiation as they move from the basal layer to the stratum corneum."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57930"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17780"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57930"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T20:53:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T20:56:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10494"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72460"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4932"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Skin and Associated Structures","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading